{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bb243778-cfce-450c-80e9-ed935b90ef63","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Backgrounded | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Resumed | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n| iOS background | `Backgrounding` (save state via `BackgroundingEventArgs.State`) |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS-specific and provides a `IPersistedState` dictionary you can write to so state survives termination.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f35191b-36e0-49b4-a10f-2087f4d8ebac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"F40F:156A76:1F2B43A:22F9FCF:69E81A2C"},"id":"4e0d7107-4c1b-4da0-b38b-bb90d9949140","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:45:41.055Z","parentId":"81b08791-3eec-48ab-a327-eb7ff0933de1"}
